Assuming you have a parent model that has many child models with tags, you can use the Spatie `tags` method to retrieve all the tags of the child models and consolidate them into a single collection of tags for the parent model.

Here's an example code snippet that demonstrates how to do this:


```php
// Get all child models associated with the parent model
$childModels = $parentModel->childModels;

// Create an empty collection to hold all the tags
$tagsCollection = collect();

// Loop through each child model and add its tags to the collection
foreach ($childModels as $childModel) {
 $tagsCollection = $tagsCollection->merge($childModel->tags);
}

// Consolidate the tags by removing duplicates
$consolidatedTags = $tagsCollection->unique();

// Assign the consolidated tags to the parent model
$parentModel->syncTags($consolidatedTags);
```
In this example, `childModels` is the relationship method on the parent model that retrieves all associated child models. `tags` is the Spatie method on the child model that retrieves all tags associated with the model.

The code loops through each child model and merges its tags with the `$tagsCollection` variable. The `merge` method is used to add the child model's tags to the collection without duplicates.

After consolidating all the tags, the code uses the `unique` method to remove any duplicates in the collection.

Finally, the `syncTags` method is used to assign the consolidated tags to the parent model. This method removes any tags from the parent model that are not in the consolidated tags collection, and adds any new tags that are not already associated with the parent model.

To display the consolidated tags in Laravel Nova, you can create a computed field on the parent model resource. Here's an example code snippet that demonstrates how to do this:


```php
namespace App\Nova;

use Laravel\Nova\Fields\Text;
use Laravel\Nova\Resource;

class ParentModelResource extends Resource
{
 // ...

 /\*\*
 \* Get the fields displayed by the resource.
 \*
 \* @param \Illuminate\Http\Request $request
 \* @return array
 \*/
 public function fields(Request $request)
 {
 return [
 // ...

 Text::make('Tags', function () {
 $tagsCollection = collect();

 foreach ($this->childModels as $childModel) {
 $tagsCollection = $tagsCollection->merge($childModel->tags);
 }

 $consolidatedTags = $tagsCollection->unique()->implode(', ');

 return $consolidatedTags;
 }),

 // ...
 ];
 }

 // ...
}
```
In this example, we've added a new `Text` field called "Tags" to the resource's `fields` method. We're using a closure to compute the field's value instead of a database column.

Inside the closure, we've replicated the logic we used to consolidate the tags in the previous example. We loop through each child model and add its tags to a collection. Then, we use the `unique` method to remove any duplicates, and the `implode` method to concatenate the tags into a single string.

Finally, we return the consolidated tags string, which will be displayed in the "Tags" field on the parent model's detail view in Nova.

To render a triangle using the Vulkan API in C++, you'll need to set up various components, such as instance, devices, swapchain, graphics pipeline, etc. Here's a basic example that demonstrates the process:


```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <stdexcept>
#include <cstdlib>
#include <cstring>
#include <vulkan/vulkan.h>

// Vertex data for the triangle
const std::vector<float> vertices = {
 -0.5f, -0.5f, 0.0f,
 0.5f, -0.5f, 0.0f,
 0.0f, 0.5f, 0.0f
};

// Shader code in SPIR-V format
const std::vector<uint32\_t> vertexShaderCode = { /\* SPIR-V code for vertex shader \*/ };
const std::vector<uint32\_t> fragmentShaderCode = { /\* SPIR-V code for fragment shader \*/ };

class TriangleRenderer {
public:
 void run() {
 initVulkan();
 mainLoop();
 cleanup();
 }

private:
 void initVulkan() {
 // Initialize Vulkan components
 createInstance();
 // ...
 }

 void mainLoop() {
 // Render the triangle
 }

 void cleanup() {
 // Clean up Vulkan resources
 vkDestroyInstance(instance, nullptr);
 }

 void createInstance() {
 // Create a Vulkan instance
 VkApplicationInfo appInfo{};
 appInfo.sType = VK_STRUCTURE_TYPE_APPLICATION_INFO;
 appInfo.pApplicationName = "Triangle Renderer";
 appInfo.applicationVersion = VK\_MAKE\_VERSION(1, 0, 0);
 appInfo.pEngineName = "No Engine";
 appInfo.engineVersion = VK\_MAKE\_VERSION(1, 0, 0);
 appInfo.apiVersion = VK_API_VERSION_1_0;

 VkInstanceCreateInfo createInfo{};
 createInfo.sType = VK_STRUCTURE_TYPE_INSTANCE_CREATE_INFO;
 createInfo.pApplicationInfo = &appInfo;

 uint32\_t extensionCount = 0;
 const char** glfwExtensions = nullptr; // Retrieve required extensions for your platform/windowing system
 createInfo.enabledExtensionCount = extensionCount;
 createInfo.ppEnabledExtensionNames = glfwExtensions;

 if (vkCreateInstance(&createInfo, nullptr, &instance) != VK_SUCCESS) {
 throw std::runtime\_error("Failed to create Vulkan instance.");
 }
 }

 VkInstance instance;
};

int main() {
 TriangleRenderer triangleRenderer;

 try {
 triangleRenderer.run();
 } catch (const std::exception& e) {
 std::cerr << "Error: " << e.what() << std::endl;
 return EXIT_FAILURE;
 }

 return EXIT_SUCCESS;
}
```
This example sets up a basic structure for a Vulkan application but does not include the full code for rendering a triangle. You'll need to fill in the missing parts, such as creating a window, selecting a physical device, creating a logical device, setting up a swap chain, creating the render pass, creating the graphics pipeline, creating framebuffers, and more.

Additionally, you'll need to provide SPIR-V formatted vertex and fragment shader code to render the triangle. You can use a tool like glslangValidator to compile your GLSL shaders to SPIR-V.

For a comprehensive tutorial on rendering a triangle using Vulkan, consider following the tutorial on vulkan-tutorial.com:

<https://vulkan-tutorial.com/Introduction>

```
interface Tab {
 label: string;
 id: string;
 active: boolean;
 link: string;
}

let tabs: Tab[] = [];

function addTab(label: string, id: string, active: boolean, link: string): void {
 let newTab: Tab = {
 label: label,
 id: id,
 active: active,
 link: link
 };
 tabs.push(newTab);
}
```
This function takes in four parameters, three of type string and one of type boolean. It creates a new tab object with properties label, id, active and link and pushes it to the tabs array.

