To properly stop a GStreamer pipeline in C++, you can use the `gst_element_set_state()` function to set the state of the pipeline to GST\_STATE\_NULL. This will stop the pipeline and release any resources it was using. To clean up the pipeline, you can then use `gst_object_unref()` to release the pipeline's resources. It's important to note that the pipeline should be in the playing or paused state before attempting to set its state to NULL, otherwise the pipeline may not clean up properly.

Here is an example of stopping a pipeline:


```
GstStateChangeReturn ret;

// Set the pipeline state to NULL
ret = gst_element_set_state (pipeline, GST_STATE_NULL);
if (ret == GST_STATE_CHANGE_FAILURE) {
 // Handle error
}

// Wait for the pipeline to complete state change
ret = gst_element_get_state (pipeline, NULL, NULL, GST_CLOCK_TIME_NONE);
if (ret == GST_STATE_CHANGE_FAILURE) {
 // Handle error
}

// Release pipeline resources
gst_object_unref (pipeline);
```
It's also good practice to do the cleanup of the pipeline elements, bus and message handlers.


```
// Remove elements from pipeline
gst\_bin\_remove\_many(GST_BIN(pipeline), src, filter, sink, NULL);

// Unreference elements
gst\_object\_unref(src);
gst\_object\_unref(filter);
gst\_object\_unref(sink);

// Remove bus watch
gst_bus_remove_watch (bus);

// Unreference bus
gst_object_unref (bus);
```

The `gst_debug_bin_to_dot_file()` function is used to create a graph of a GStreamer pipeline in the Graphviz dot format. The graph can be visualized using Graphviz software, which can be useful for debugging pipeline issues.

Here's an example of how to use `gst_debug_bin_to_dot_file()` to save a graph of your pipeline to a file:


```
#include <gst/gst.h>

int main(int argc, char \*argv[]) {
 GstElement *pipeline;
 // Initialize GStreamer
 gst_init(&argc, &argv);

 // Create pipeline
 pipeline = gst_pipeline_new("my\_pipeline");

 // Add elements to pipeline
 // ...

 // Link elements
 // ...

 // Save pipeline to dot file
 gst_debug_bin_to_dot_file(GST_BIN(pipeline), GST_DEBUG_GRAPH_SHOW_ALL, "pipeline");

 // Release pipeline resources
 gst_object_unref(pipeline);

 return 0;
}
```
This will create a file named "pipeline.dot" in the current working directory that contains a graph of the pipeline. You can then use Graphviz software to visualize the graph.

You can also use GST\_DEBUG\_BIN\_TO\_DOT\_FILE\_WITH\_TS environment variable to save the dot file with timestamp, it will be saved in the directory specified in the GST\_DEBUG\_FILE\_DIR environment variable.

Additionally, you can use GST\_DEBUG\_DUMP\_DOT\_DIR to specify the directory where the dot files will be saved.

You should be careful when using the `gst_debug_bin_to_dot_file()` in a production environment because it can create large files that take up a lot of disk space.

`gst_element_get_state()` is a function in the GStreamer library that is used to retrieve the current state of a GStreamer element.

The function takes two arguments:

1. A pointer to the GstElement for which the state should be retrieved.
2. A pointer to a GstState variable that will be set to the current state of the element.

The function returns a GstStateChangeReturn value, which can be one of the following:

* GST\_STATE\_CHANGE\_SUCCESS: The state change was successful.
* GST\_STATE\_CHANGE\_ASYNC: The state change is happening asynchronously.
* GST\_STATE\_CHANGE\_FAILURE: The state change failed.
* GST\_STATE\_CHANGE\_NO\_PREROLL: The element doesn't support prerolling.

Here's an example of how to use `gst_element_get_state()` to retrieve the current state of a pipeline:


```
#include <gst/gst.h>

int main(int argc, char \*argv[]) {
 GstElement *pipeline;
 GstState state;
 GstStateChangeReturn ret;

 // Initialize GStreamer
 gst_init(&argc, &argv);

 // Create pipeline
 pipeline = gst_pipeline_new("my\_pipeline");

 // Get the current state of the pipeline
 ret = gst_element_get_state(pipeline, &state, NULL, GST_CLOCK_TIME_NONE);

 if (ret == GST_STATE_CHANGE_SUCCESS) {
 printf("The current state of the pipeline is: %s\n", gst_element_state_get_name(state));
 } else {
 printf("Failed to get the state of the pipeline\n");
 }

 // Release pipeline resources
 gst_object_unref(pipeline);

 return 0;
}
```
This will print the current state of the pipeline (e.g. "NULL", "PLAYING", "PAUSED", etc.) if the state change was successful. If the state change failed, it will print "Failed to get the state of the pipeline".

It's important to note that `gst_element_get_state()` is an async function, so the returned state is not guaranteed to be the final state of the pipeline. Additionally, you should use gst\_element\_get\_state() only after the pipeline is started, otherwise you will get GST\_STATE\_CHANGE\_FAILURE.

Using the GstBus to listen for the end-of-stream message in GStreamer can be done in a few steps:

1. Create a GstBus from the pipeline:


```
GstBus *bus = gst\_pipeline\_get\_bus(GST_PIPELINE(pipeline));
```
2. Add a bus watch to the bus: This will enable you to receive messages from the bus and process them as needed.


```
gst\_bus\_add\_watch(bus, bus_callback, user_data);
```
3. Create a bus callback function: This function will be called whenever a message is received on the bus. The bus callback should check for the end-of-stream message and take appropriate action when it is received.


```
static gboolean bus\_callback(GstBus \*bus, GstMessage \*message, gpointer user\_data) {
 switch (GST\_MESSAGE\_TYPE(message)) {
 case GST\_MESSAGE\_EOS:
 /\* end-of-stream message received, stop the pipeline \*/
 gst\_element\_set\_state(pipeline, GST\_STATE\_NULL);
 break;
 /\* other message types can be handled here as needed \*/
 }
 return TRUE;
}
```
4. Start the pipeline: This will start the pipeline processing data, and the bus callback will be called whenever a message is received on the bus.


```
gst\_element\_set\_state(pipeline, GST_STATE_PLAYING);
```
5. Wait for the pipeline to reach the GST\_STATE\_NULL state:


```
GstStateChangeReturn ret;
GstState state;
ret = gst_element_get_state(pipeline, &state, NULL, GST_CLOCK_TIME_NONE);
```
6. Unref the pipeline and remove the bus watch


```
gst\_object\_unref(pipeline);
gst\_bus\_remove\_watch(bus);
```
This way, using the GstBus will ensure that the pipeline has finished processing all data before stopping it, and cleanup resources correctly.

It's important to note that you should always remove the bus watch when you no longer need it to avoid memory leaks.

Here is some sample code in TypeScript that creates a button that, when clicked, sends a GraphQL query to a server that downloads a zip file containing files from Google Storage and a CSV file from a Postgres table:


```
import * as React from 'react';
import { useMutation } from '@apollo/client';
import gql from 'graphql-tag';

const DOWNLOAD\_ZIP\_MUTATION = gql`
 mutation DownloadZip($input: DownloadZipInput!) {
 downloadZip(input: $input) {
 success
 message
 file
 }
 }
`;

interface DownloadZipInput {
 googleStorageFileIds: string[];
 postgresTableName: string;
}

interface DownloadZipResult {
 success: boolean;
 message: string;
 file: string;
}

const DownloadButton: React.FC<{}> = () => {
 const [downloadZip, { data }] = useMutation<DownloadZipResult, DownloadZipInput>(DOWNLOAD\_ZIP\_MUTATION);

 const handleClick = () => {
 const input: DownloadZipInput = {
 googleStorageFileIds: ['file1', 'file2'],
 postgresTableName: 'table1',
 };
 downloadZip({ variables: { input } });
 };

 return (
 <button onClick={handleClick}>
 Download Zip
 </button>
 );
};

export default DownloadButton;
```
This code uses the `useMutation` hook from the `@apollo/client` library to execute a GraphQL mutation that downloads the zip file. The mutation takes an input object with two fields: `googleStorageFileIds`, which is an array of IDs of the files to be included in the zip file, and `postgresTableName`, which is the name of the Postgres table from which to generate a CSV file.

When the button is clicked, the `handleClick` function is called, which sends the GraphQL mutation with the specified input. The result of the mutation is stored in the `data` variable, which can be used to display a message or link to the downloaded zip file.

