```
// Import the necessary modules
const Jimp = require('jimp');

// Load the images and store them in an array
const images = [Jimp.read('image1.png'), Jimp.read('image2.png'), ...];

// Function to fade between the images
async function fadeBetweenImages(images, values) {
 // Create a new blank image
 const result = new Jimp(images[0].bitmap.width, images[0].bitmap.height);

 // Loop through the images and values and fade between them
 for (let i = 0; i < images.length; i++) {
 // Get the current image and value
 const image = images[i];
 const value = values[i];

 // Fade the current image into the result image
 result.composite(image, 0, 0, {
 mode: Jimp.BLEND\_SOURCE\_OVER,
 opacitySource: value,
 opacityDest: 1.0 - value
 });
 }

 // Save the result image
 await result.write('result.png');
}

// Fade between the images using the given values
fadeBetweenImages(images, [0.3, 0.7, 0.1, ...]);
```
This code uses the Jimp library to load the images and fade between them. The `fadeBetweenImages()` function takes two arguments: an array of images and an array of values. It creates a new blank image and then loops through the images and values, fading each image into the result image according to the corresponding value. Finally, it saves the result image.

You can adjust the amount of fading by modifying the values in the `fadeBetweenImages()` function call. For example, if you want the first image to fade in more and the second image to fade out more, you could use the following values: `[0.7, 0.3, ...]`.

