An instance variable is a variable that is declared in a class but is not marked as `static`. It is called an "instance" variable because each object (also known as an instance) of the class has its own separate copy of the variable.

Instance variables define the state of an object and hold data that is unique to each object. They can be of any data type (e.g. int, double, String, etc.) and can have any access modifier (public, private, protected, or default). Instance variables can be accessed and modified by any method within the class.

For example, consider the following `Car` class:


```typescript
public class Car {
 private String make;
 private String model;
 private int year;
 private double price;

 // constructor
 public Car(String make, String model, int year, double price) {
 this.make = make;
 this.model = model;
 this.year = year;
 this.price = price;
 }

 // getters and setters
 public String getMake() {
 return make;
 }

 public void setMake(String make) {
 this.make = make;
 }

 public String getModel() {
 return model;
 }

 public void setModel(String model) {
 this.model = model;
 }

 public int getYear() {
 return year;
 }

 public void setYear(int year) {
 this.year = year;
 }

 public double getPrice() {
 return price;
 }

 public void setPrice(double price) {
 this.price = price;
 }
}
```
In this example, `make`, `model`, `year`, and `price` are instance variables of the `Car` class. Each `Car` object created from this class will have its own separate copy of these variables. The `getters` and `setters` methods are used to access and modify these instance variables from outside the class.

Overall, instance variables play an important role in defining the state of an object and storing data that is unique to each instance of a class.

